The architecture of the proposed 2nd-level of control i.e., HFLAG-MRAC is shown in Fig. 9. The proposed HFLAG-MRAC acquires its reference signal d(t=r)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$d(t = r)$$\end{document} from the RCC unit. The aim of the HFLAG-MRAC design is to achieve improved transient performance in MPPT, by handling the faster converter dynamics of the non-linear PV systems under changing environment conditions, without the need for high-static adaptation gain. In the first level of the proposed MPPT control the RCC, utilizes the high frequency content and correlate it with the switching function to affect control11.Figure 9
Architecture of 2nd-level of MPPT control (Novel HFLAG-MRAC controller).

In a similar manner as RCC, the proposed HFLAG-MRAC utilizes the high-frequency (ripple) content of the tracking error to adjust its gain in response to the variations in inputs and yields critically-damped PV system characteristics under rapidly changing conditions. In PV systems, these high-frequency (ripple) contents of the tracking error are the actual representation of rapid variations appearing in input parameters due to change in solar insolation, temperature, and thus, in duty-cycle dt\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$d\left( t \right)$$\end{document}. Therefore, for an accurate modelling and MPPT control, the gain of the second-level of control must be adjusted in accordance with the high-frequency (ripple) content of the tracking error, instead of overall tracking error.

