The overall derived HFLAG-MRAC rules can be summarized as follows:39δ˙1=-μδ1+up,δ˙2=-μδ2+yp,Φ˙=-αΦ+δ,δ=r,δ1,δ2,ypT,up=φTδ+φ˙TΦ=φTδ-ΦTΓtProjφ,e0Φ,φ˙=-Γ1+Γ2e¯hfTΓhf-1e¯hfProjφ,e0Φ.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \dot{\delta }_{1} & = - \mu \delta_{1} + u_{p} , \\ \dot{\delta }_{2} & = - \mu \delta_{2} + y_{p} , \\ {\dot{\Phi }} & = - \alpha {\Phi } + \delta ,\quad \delta = \left[ {r,\delta_{1} ,\delta_{2} ,y_{p} } \right]{ }^{T} , \\ u_{p} & = \varphi^{T} \delta + \dot{\varphi }^{T} {\Phi } = \varphi^{T} \delta - \Phi^{T} {\Gamma }\left( {\text{t}} \right){ }Proj{ }\left( {\varphi ,e_{0} {\Phi }} \right), \\ \dot{\varphi } & = - \left( {{\Gamma }_{1} + {\Gamma }_{2} { }\overline{e}_{hf}^{T} {{ \Gamma }}_{hf}^{ - 1} \overline{e}_{hf} } \right){ }Proj{ }\left( {\varphi ,e_{0} {\Phi }} \right). \\ \end{aligned}$$\end{document}

The update laws for proposed HFLAG-MRAC controller mentioned in (39) can be interpreted as, the proposed controller has two distinct gain parameters terms for adjustment. First term is static gain term Γ1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\Gamma }_{1}$$\end{document}, which should be less for ideal controller design. It is the gain when error ceases to zero i.e., the static gain Γ1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\Gamma }_{1}$$\end{document} is the minimum gain required for controller to under no or small variations in input. The second term Γ2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\Gamma }_{2}$$\end{document} is the adjustable gain term, which is a function of high-frequency content of the tracking (output) error. In other words, Γ2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\Gamma }_{2}$$\end{document} is adjusted in response to the variations in environmental conditions i.e., rapidly changing external input perturbations.

